{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_kale_ver01/data/2017236974/00279558078/1945121301/1176.xml":{"full_text":"Survey Reveals Misunderstanding j\nAbout Two Social Insurance Plans\nInquiries made recently by field\noffices of the Social Security Board\nin this region, show that less than\nhalf of the 200 people interviwed,\nknow the difference between the\ntwo insurance plans under the\nSocial Security Act. Many of\nthem believed that the one per\ncent social security tax, which a\nwage earner pays for Old-Age and\nSurvivors Insurance would entitle\nhim to Unemployment Compensat\nion benefits, in case he should lose\nhis job.\nRuth G. Duffey, manager of the\nRocky Mount office of the Social\nSecurity Board, explained that the\nSocial Security tax wljich is paid\nby workers and by employers in\nbusiness and industry is collected\nby the Federal government and\nplaced in a trust fund from which\nOld-Age and Survivors Insurance\nbenefits are paid. This plan makes\nit possible for wage earners, dur\ning their working years, to build\nup advanced protection for them\nselves and for their families. The\nbenefits are based on the worker\u2019s\nown wages in jobs that come un\nder the law.\nUnempoyment Compenstion\u2014\nwhich is sometimes called job in\nsurance\u2014is administered by the\nState, with Federal aid and co\noperation. No wage earner in this\nstate pays any Unemployment\nCompensation tax. Business and\nindustrial concerns which employ\n8 or more workers, pay all of the\nUnemployment Compensation tax\nin this State. It is their employees\nwho may receive Unemployment\nbenefits when they lose their jobs.\nThe purpose of Unemployment\nCompensation is to furnish some\nincome to insured workers, during\nperiods when they axe without\nwork, untill they can get other\njobs. Payments are not equal to\nthe worker\u2019s regular wages, but\nthey will help tide him over\nuntill he can get back to work.\nMen or women, covered by the\nlaw, who have lost their jobs,\nshould call at their nearest local\nU. S. Employment Service office,\nregister for a job, and file claim\nfor Unemployment Compensation.\nThe address may be secured from\nyour Post Office.\nClaimants for Old-Age and Sur\nvivors Insurance benefits should\napply at the field office of the\nSocial Security Board, located at\nRocky Mount, N. C.\nA representive of this office\nwill be in Roanoke Rapids at the\nEmployment Office every Tuesday\nat 2:00 p. m.\nI'* 'A' \"A\" \"A\" \"A\" 'A' 'A' 'A' 'A' 'A' \u2018A\u2019 'A'\nI\nUnique Air Service i\n_c\nWASHINGTON\u2014\u201cThe sky is the\nlimit,\u201d is a phrase being proved\nextra true in aviation. The amaz- t\ning progress of air transportation -j\nis vividly shown in the plans for\nbroadening the scope of commer\ncial operations as soon as the tran\nsition to peace-time conditions\npermits.\nDelivery of new automobiles by\nhuge glider trains of the sky is\nonly one of the more striking en\nterprises for which applications are\njust waiting to be given the green\nlight by the Civil Aeronautics\nBoard. The list according to the\nAir Transport Association of\nAmerica, includes:\nFlying ambulances and funeral 1\nplanes.\nArmored airships for safe dis\npatch of currency and valu-\nables.\nBig tank planes for shipment\nof gasoline and oil.\nBus and taxi service, using\nboth helicopters and conven\ntional models.\nDeliveries of medicine, of food,\nand of department store\nmerchandise.\nSightseeing specialists.\nFly-yourself systems.\nDelivery of new or \u201cused\u201d air\nplanes to buyers or dealers.\nMany war veterans who have\ngained invaluable experience flying\nin the war are in the forefront of\nthese projects. There are some\nwhole groups which served togeth\ner in battle and plan to stick to\ngether as partners in the airline\nbusiness.\nThe mightiest Army in the j\nWorid invites you to join them i\nn keeping the peace that was\nwon in sweat and tears and blood\non the battle fields of the World\nIf you are between the ages of\n18 and 34. or veteran of World\nWar II. you can enlist or reenlist\nin the Regular Army of the\nUnited States. The Army will give\nyou an opportunity to travel, a t\nchance at an interesting career or j\nan education to fit you better for j\nfuture civilian occupation or pro- h\nfession. Apply now at your near- j\nest recruiting station. In Roanoke\nRapids, the recruiting station is\nlocated in the Roanoke Rapids j\nArmory.\niT Vs.\u2019 A* A\u2019 A\" A' A A\" A* A' AAV\nEnfield PTA\nrSolds Meet\nEnfield The November meet\nig of the P. T. A. was held in the\nInfield School Auditorium Thurs\nay evening of last week at 7:30\n\u2019clock with Mrs. Robert Whitaker\nresiding. She reported a neat\nddition to the treasury funds from\nhe sale of waste pa.per and the\n'hanksgiving basket.\nThe Membership Chairman, Mrs.\nVilliam Neville, made an appeal\nor new members and dues, sta.t\nng that the P. T. A. is a joint\nnterprise, teachers and parents\n/orking for the betterment of\noys and girls.\nMrs. R. E. Shervette, Jr., asked\nhe co-operation of the P. T. A\ne a drive to bring the North\nlarolina Symphony to Halifax\nlounty .in the near future.\nThe following program was en\noyed: The Star Spangled Banner;\nl Litany for Parents was used as\nesponsive reading, the theme bo\nng \"Rejoice that you have child\nen in your homes and in your\nlass rooms;\u201d C. D. Graham, John\nJcGwigan, Frank Pittman and S.\nl. Dunn sang a quartette.\nThe 10th grade, under the direc\nion of Miss Phillips, gave a bur\nlesque \u201cRomeo and Juliet.\u201d\nMr. Hickman was winner in a\nWhistling Contest, first eating a\ncracker.\nCOOKED A FINE\nDINNER; THEN\nTHREW IT TO DOG\nOne lady recently stated that she\nused to throw her own dinner to\nthe dog most of the time. It made\nher sick just to look at anything\nto eat. She was swollen with gas,\nfull of bloat, bad headaches, felt\nvorn out and was badly constipat\n'd. Finally she got INNER-AID\nind says she now eats everything\nn sight and digests it perfectly.\nSowels are regular and normal.\nShe is enjoying life once more and\n\u2019eels like \u201csome other womai^*\ndnce taking this New Compound.\nINNER-AID contains 12 Great\nSerbs; they cleanse bowels, clear\n;as from stomach, act on sluggish\niver and kidneys. Miserable peo\nple soon feel different all over. So\nlon\u2019t go on suffering! Get INNER\nAID. Sold by all drug stores here\nn Halifax County.\u2014(Adv.) (C)\nCHICK NS!\nt Every Saturday, 9 A. M. to 6 P. M.\nat\n15 EAST NINTH SHEET\nEvery Day at our Residence on Rolling Road,\nROANOKE CHICKEN RANCH\n\u2022v\u2022 \u2022jus Vil* \u2018liV W Vii* Vh *riV \"A* VV W V&l jAl jAl A' A' A*\ny;& y;+ y;* ypt >.s\u00a3 y* v^. y.+ y;,jt >k. zMsyfe;\nTHE CHIMNEY CORNER 1\ngj 1009 ROANOKE AVENUE J:\n*_^i\n;s>:\ni^i\nis Christmas Suggestions j$\nH CHRISTMAS CARDS_$ .05 to .25 Jj\njS VASES AND FLOWER M\nBOWLS_ .60 to 5.00 88\nPERSONAL STATIONERY _ .60 to 2.00\nj*| LUSTREWARE _ 1.29 to 6.95 88\n3S WASTEBASKETS_ 1.39 to 6.95 ij;\nIjjj PICTURES_ .75 to 6.95 88\niS MUSIC BOXES_10.00 to 17.95\nTRAYS AND STANDS_ 6.95 to 17.95 88\n)S COMPACTS_ 1.95 to 6.95 j#\nHANDKERCHIEFS_ .25 to 2.00\nis 15:\njs\nAND FOR THE LITTLE FOLKS\n:s\nDolls Games Puzzles Books Toys 88\nsp..\nHf,\n*tv\n\ne:\n\n\n\ne\u00a3\nfrom \u2014-----_ l\u00ae!\nSandlin's Flower Shop if;\nS; Let us solve your Christmas shopping problems. Give Flowers. Our :S\ncarefully grown potted plants are ready for immediate and Christ\n0 mas delivery. Please book your order for Christmas plants early.\n4 CYCLAMENS PRIMROSES\nPOIN SETT AS BEGONIAS\nAZALEAS (for Christmas delivery only)\n<8 _____. p.\nI This Week\u2019s Special in Cut Flowers i\u00ae:\n5 I x PICARDY GLADIOLAS :J:\n1 SANDLIN\u2019S I\nI FLOWER SHOP l\ngg\ng\u00a3 \u201cWe Deliver Anywhere in the City\u201d\ng\u00a3 639 HENRY STREET TEL. R-790-1 j\u00a3","height":"21540","width":"14168"}}
